natural_language_question: Categorize products by price range and count each
correct_sql: SELECT CASE WHEN UnitPrice < 20 THEN 'Budget' WHEN UnitPrice BETWEEN 20 AND 50 THEN 'Mid-range' ELSE 'Premium' END AS PriceCategory, COUNT(*) AS ProductCount FROM products GROUP BY CASE WHEN UnitPrice < 20 THEN 'Budget' WHEN UnitPrice BETWEEN 20 AND 50 THEN 'Mid-range' ELSE 'Premium' END ORDER BY ProductCount DESC
correct_result: [{"PriceCategory": "Budget", "ProductCount": 39}, {"PriceCategory": "Mid-range", "ProductCount": 31}, {"PriceCategory": "Premium", "ProductCount": 7}]

natural_language_question: Classify products by stock level
correct_sql: SELECT CASE WHEN UnitsInStock = 0 THEN 'Out of Stock' WHEN UnitsInStock < 10 THEN 'Low Stock' WHEN UnitsInStock < 50 THEN 'Medium Stock' ELSE 'High Stock' END AS StockLevel, COUNT(*) AS ProductCount FROM products GROUP BY CASE WHEN UnitsInStock = 0 THEN 'Out of Stock' WHEN UnitsInStock < 10 THEN 'Low Stock' WHEN UnitsInStock < 50 THEN 'Medium Stock' ELSE 'High Stock' END ORDER BY ProductCount DESC
correct_result: [{"StockLevel": "Medium Stock", "ProductCount": 42}, {"StockLevel": "High Stock", "ProductCount": 23}, {"StockLevel": "Low Stock", "ProductCount": 7}, {"StockLevel": "Out of Stock", "ProductCount": 5}]

natural_language_question: Classify orders by freight cost and count
correct_sql: SELECT CASE WHEN Freight < 10 THEN 'Low' WHEN Freight BETWEEN 10 AND 50 THEN 'Medium' ELSE 'High' END AS FreightCategory, COUNT(*) AS OrderCount FROM orders GROUP BY CASE WHEN Freight < 10 THEN 'Low' WHEN Freight BETWEEN 10 AND 50 THEN 'Medium' ELSE 'High' END ORDER BY OrderCount DESC
correct_result: [{"FreightCategory": "High", "OrderCount": 360}, {"FreightCategory": "Medium", "OrderCount": 294}, {"FreightCategory": "Low", "OrderCount": 176}]

natural_language_question: Show customers who have spent more than the average customer
correct_sql: SELECT c.CustomerID, c.CompanyName, (SELECT SUM(od.UnitPrice * od.Quantity * (1 - od.Discount)) FROM orders o JOIN "Order Details" od ON o.OrderID = od.OrderID WHERE o.CustomerID = c.CustomerID) AS TotalSpent FROM customers c WHERE (SELECT SUM(od.UnitPrice * od.Quantity * (1 - od.Discount)) FROM orders o JOIN "Order Details" od ON o.OrderID = od.OrderID WHERE o.CustomerID = c.CustomerID) > (SELECT AVG(CustomerSpent) FROM (SELECT SUM(od.UnitPrice * od.Quantity * (1 - od.Discount)) AS CustomerSpent FROM orders o JOIN "Order Details" od ON o.OrderID = od.OrderID GROUP BY o.CustomerID)) ORDER BY TotalSpent DESC

natural_language_question: Find the most expensive product in each category
correct_sql: SELECT p1.CategoryID, c.CategoryName, p1.ProductName, p1.UnitPrice FROM products p1 JOIN categories c ON p1.CategoryID = c.CategoryID WHERE p1.UnitPrice = (SELECT MAX(p2.UnitPrice) FROM products p2 WHERE p2.CategoryID = p1.CategoryID) ORDER BY c.CategoryName

natural_language_question: Find customers who ordered all products from the Dairy Products category
correct_sql: SELECT c.CustomerID, c.CompanyName FROM customers c WHERE (SELECT COUNT(DISTINCT p.ProductID) FROM products p JOIN "Order Details" od ON p.ProductID = od.ProductID JOIN orders o ON od.OrderID = o.OrderID WHERE o.CustomerID = c.CustomerID AND p.CategoryID = (SELECT CategoryID FROM categories WHERE CategoryName = 'Dairy Products')) = (SELECT COUNT(*) FROM products WHERE CategoryID = (SELECT CategoryID FROM categories WHERE CategoryName = 'Dairy Products')) ORDER BY c.CompanyName
correct_result: [{"CustomerID": "ERNSH", "CompanyName": "Ernst Handel"}]
